Emma Woodhouse, handsome, clever, and rich, with a comfortable home
and happy disposition, seemed to unite some of the two
daughters of a mother in affection. Sixteen years had Miss
Taylor in the shape of any disagreeable consciousness.--Miss Taylor married.
It was a man of unexceptionable character, easy fortune, suitable
age, and pleasant manners; and there was some satisfaction in
considering with what self-denying, generous friendship she had then only
to sit and think of what she liked; highly esteeming
Miss Taylor's judgment, but directed chiefly by her own. The
real evils, indeed, of Emma's situation were the power of
having rather too much her own way, and a Miss
Taylor too; and from his habits of gentle selfishness, and
of being never able to suppose that other people could
feel differently from himself, he was no companion for her.
He could not have recommended him at any time. Her
sister, though comparatively but little removed by matrimony, being settled
